AGI -&nbsp; The President of the Giorgia Meloni Council arrived at Downing Street for the bilateral meeting with British Prime Minister Keir Starmer, who welcomed it in front of the entrance door. At the heart of the talks between the two leaders will be Ukraine, but also the issue of migration and that of the Common Defense.
<div </div
"We are all very committed to the goal we all want to achieve, that is, a just and lasting peace for Ukraine." So the President of the Council, Giorgia Meloni, during the institutional greetings at Downing Street, before the beginning of the bilateral meeting with the British Prime Minister, Keir Starmer.
In the early afternoon Meloni will go to the Lancaster House for the summit on Ukraine and the common security to which will take part over 15 heads of state or government, as well as representatives of NATO and EU. In front of Downing Street there is a group of protesters who wave Ukrainian flags and the EU and show anti-Putin.&nbsp signs;
"At this moment it is very important that we speak, that we coordinate. Thank you for calling the summit." He said the President of the Council, Giorgia Meloni, in the institutional greetings with British Prime Minister Keir Starmer before the bilateral meeting at Downing Street.
"I believe it is very important that we avoid the risk that the West divides and I believe that Italy and the United Kingdom can play an important role in building bridges on this point: for this I have proposed a meeting between the United States and European leaders, because if we split up we will all be weaker," added Meloni.
&nbsp;"I am very pleased that we build our partnership from month to month on different central points - he continued - I am sure that we can do even better on issues such as security, defense, energy and fight against irregular immigration and traffickers of human beings. We need new tools and new ideas to ensure the safety of our citizens."
<h2>Starmer at Meloni: "We have similar approaches"</h2>
"It is great that you are here at this crucial moment and it was fantastic a few months ago in Rome to celebrate the closeness of our nations and to talk about the common concerns we have. Today we will talk about economics, migrations, security: we address these issues with very similar approaches." So the British premier, Keir Starmer, in the institutional greetings with Premier Giorgia Meloni at Downing Street.&nbsp;
