AGI -&nbsp; British Prime Minister Keir Starmer invited over a dozen European and EU leaders to a summit tomorrow in London to "bring forward" the action on Ukraine and security >. Downing Street announced it. Starmer will preside over a video conference in the morning with the Baltic nations, before welcoming Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky at Downing Street. The leaders of all continental Europe, including France, Germany, Denmark and Italy, as well as Turkey, NATO and the European Union, were invited to the London summit, added the office of the British Prime Minister.
Fresco of his talks with US President Donald Trump at the White House, Starmer also invited leaders of the Netherlands, Norway, Poland, Spain, Finland, Sweden, Czech Republic and Romania at the summit. The head of NATO Mark Rutte and the leaders of the EU Ursula don der Leyen and Antonio Costa should also participate. Also confirmed the participation of the first Canadian Minister &nbsp;Justin Trudeau.
&nbsp;
Starmer will hold individual talks at Downing Street with the Italian Council President Giorgia&nbsp;Meloni&nbsp; before the start of the summit.> His office said that the meeting will be based on the Paris talks hosted by French leader Macron earlier this month and will focus on "strengthening Ukraine's position, including continuous military support and increased economic pressure on Russia".
The &nbsp;vertice&nbsp; will once again emphasize the need for a "strong and lasting agreement that guarantees permanent peace" and will discuss "the next steps in planning strong security guarantees". Starmer, while insisting again on the fact that Ukraine must be part of any negotiations to end the three-year war with Russia, will also recognize "the need for Europe to play its part in the defence and move forward for the sake of collective security". During yesterday's talks at the White House, Trump took a softer tone on the Ukrainian crisis, but refused to give firm commitments on the security guarantees of the United States, which Europe desperately needs.
Trump, who alarmed European capitals with his approach to Russia, said that there were "many progress" towards an agreement to end the conflict in Ukraine and that negotiations are at a crucial stage.
